// Block stages carrying scalars use in-process typed transport with a per-pipe
// value queue, so each `yield`ed value is a distinct framed message — not bytes
// concatenated into one buffer. A consumer block that reads `&0` a fixed number
// of times therefore consumes exactly that many values and discards the rest.
//
// Here the producer yields three Ints but the consumer reads `&0` only twice,
// so the pipeline emits the first two values (1, 2) as `12`. Under the old
// byte-pipe path this boundary buffered "123" and a single `&0` read returned
// the whole thing; per-value framing is what makes this print `12`.

{ yield 1; yield 2; yield 3; } | { yield &0; yield &0 }
